M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Master revenue and retention metrics to understand SaaS business momentum, evaluate product-market fit, and make data-driven decisions about growth investments. Use this to calculate key metrics, inte
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|This is not a business intelligence tool—it's a framework for PMs to understand which metrics matter, how to calculate them correctly, and what actions to take based on the numbers.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|The "top-line" metrics that measure how much money the business generates.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Revenue** — Total money earned from selling products/services before expenses. The "top line" of the income statement.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Every feature should connect to revenue (direct or indirect). If you can't articulate revenue impact, prioritization becomes impossible.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** Sum of all customer payments in a period
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Growth rate matters more than absolute number (ctx-dependent by stage)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**ARPU (Average Revenue Per User)** — Average revenue generated per individual user.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Measures per-seat monetization effectiveness. Critical for seat-based pricing models.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `Total Revenue / Total Users`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Varies by model; track trend more than absolute value
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **B2C SaaS:** $5-50/month typical; B2B: $50-500+/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**ARPA (Average Revenue Per Account)** — Average revenue generated per customer account.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Measures account-level deal size. Critical for account-based pricing models.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `MRR / Active Accounts`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** SMB SaaS: $100-$1K/month; Mid-market: $1K-$10K; Enterprise: $10K+
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**ARPA/ARPU Analysis** — Using both metrics together to understand monetization.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Prevents packaging mistakes. High ARPA + low ARPU = undermonetized per seat. Low ARPA + high ARPU = small deal sizes.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Example:** $10K ARPA with 100 seats = $100 ARPU (reasonable). $10K ARPA with 1,000 seats = $10 ARPU (leaving money on table).
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**ACV (Annual Contract Value)** — Annualized recurring revenue per contract (excludes one-time fees).
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Compares economics across different contract structures. Enables sales compensation design and segment analysis.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `Annual Recurring Revenue per Contract` (don't include setup fees, professional services)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** SMB: $5K-$25K; Mid-market: $25K-$100K; Enterprise: $100K+
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**MRR/ARR (Monthly/Annual Recurring Revenue)** — Predictable recurring revenue normalized to monthly or annual.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** The heartbeat of subscription businesses. Valued at 5-10x+ multiples. Track components (new, expansion, churn).
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `MRR = Sum of all recurring subscription revenue per month`; `ARR = MRR × 12`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Growth rate and quality matter; track new MRR, expansion MRR, churned MRR, contracted MRR
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Gross vs. Net Revenue** — Gross revenue before vs. net revenue after discounts, refunds, credits.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Discounts and refunds can hide bad acquisition quality or product problems.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `Net Revenue = Gross Revenue - Discounts - Refunds - Credits`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Refunds >10% is a red flag; track by acquisition channel
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Metrics that measure how well you keep and grow existing customers.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Churn Rate** — Percentage of customers who cancel in a period.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Silent killer of SaaS. Undermines all acquisition efforts. 5% monthly churn = 46% annual churn (compounding).
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `Customers Lost in Period / Starting Customers`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark (Monthly):** <2% great, 2-5% acceptable, >5% crisis
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark (Annual):** <10% great, 10-30% acceptable, >30% crisis
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Note:** Logo churn (customer count) differs from revenue churn (dollar amount)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**NRR (Net Revenue Retention)** — Revenue retention from existing customers including expansion and contraction.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** The holy grail metric. NRR >100% means you grow without new logos. Highly valued by investors.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `(Starting ARR + Expansion - Churn - Contraction) / Starting ARR × 100`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** >120% excellent, 100-120% good, 90-100% acceptable, <90% problem
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Example:** Start with $1M ARR, add $300K expansion, lose $100K to churn = $1.2M / $1M = 120% NRR
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Expansion Revenue** — Additional revenue from existing customers (upsells, cross-sells, usage growth).
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Most capital-efficient revenue (no CAC). Should drive NRR >100%.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `Sum of upsells + cross-sells + usage increases from existing customers`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Should represent 20-30% of total revenue; drives NRR >100%
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quick Ratio (SaaS)** — Revenue gains vs. revenue losses.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Shows if you're building on solid ground or running on a treadmill.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `(New MRR + Expansion MRR) / (Churned MRR + Contraction MRR)`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** >4 excellent, 2-4 healthy, <2 leaky bucket
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Revenue Mix Analysis** — Breakdown of revenue by product, segment, or channel.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Identifies which products fund the business and where to invest. Reveals concentration risk.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Formula:** `Product/Segment Revenue / Total Revenue × 100`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** No single product >60% ideal; diversification reduces risk
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Cohort Analysis** — Group customers by join date and track behavior over time.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Why PMs care:** Blended metrics hide critical trends. Shows whether business is improving or degrading.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Method:** Track retention, expansion, and LTV by cohort (e.g., "Jan 2024 cohort")
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Benchmark:** Recent cohorts should perform same or better than old cohorts
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Not profit metrics:** Revenue is top-line, not bottom-line. High revenue with negative margins is a disaster.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Not vanity metrics:** Total revenue growth means nothing if driven by unsustainable discounting or margin-destroying deals.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Not blended averages:** ARPU that averages $10 SMB and $1,000 enterprise customers hides segment economics.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- **Not isolated numbers:** Churn rate alone doesn't tell the story—need to see cohort trends and NRR.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Use these when:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Evaluating overall business health and product-market fit
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Comparing performance across time periods or cohorts
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Prioritizing features with direct monetization paths (ARPU impact, expansion enablers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Communicating with leadership, board, or investors
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Assessing retention problems (churn analysis, cohort degradation)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Measuring pricing or packaging changes (ARPU/ARPA shifts)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Don't use these when:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Evaluating profitability (use margin metrics instead)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Assessing capital efficiency (use LTV:CAC, payback period)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Making product investment decisions without cost ctx (revenue alone isn't ROI)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Comparing across wildly different business models without normalization
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Use the templates in `template.md` to calculate your core revenue metrics.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Revenue = Sum of all customer payments in period
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Month 1 payments: $100,000
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Revenue = $100,000
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is this gross or net revenue? (Clarify if discounts/refunds are included)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is revenue growing cohort-over-cohort, or just from new customer adds?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- What's the revenue growth rate vs. headcount/cost growth rate?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|ARPU = Total Revenue / Total Users
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Total Revenue: $100,000/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Total Users: 2,000
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPU = $100,000 / 2,000 = $50/user/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is ARPU growing or shrinking over time?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is ARPU growth from price increases or mix shift (losing small customers)?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- How does ARPU vary by cohort? (Are new customers less valuable?)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|ARPA = MRR / Active Accounts
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- MRR: $100,000
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Active Accounts: 200
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPA = $100,000 / 200 = $500/account/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is ARPA growing from expansion or just larger new deals?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- How does ARPA compare across customer segments?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is ARPA high but ARPU low? (Undermonetized per seat)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|ARPA = MRR / Active Accounts
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|ARPU = MRR / Total Users
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Average Seats per Account = ARPA / ARPU
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPA: $500/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPU: $50/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Average Seats: $500 / $50 = 10 seats/account
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Are you monetizing per seat effectively?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Could you charge more per seat (raise ARPU)?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Could you expand seat count per account (raise ARPA)?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|ACV = Annual Recurring Revenue per Contract
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|(Exclude one-time fees like setup, professional services)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Customer signs 3-year contract for $300K total
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ACV = $300K / 3 years = $100K/year
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- How does ACV vary by segment (SMB vs. Enterprise)?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is ACV growing over time (moving upmarket)?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Does ACV justify sales team cost structure?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|MRR = Sum of all recurring monthly subscriptions
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|ARR = MRR × 12
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Track components:
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- New MRR (from new customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Expansion MRR (from upsells/cross-sells)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Churned MRR (from lost customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Contraction MRR (from downgrades)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Starting MRR: $500K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- New MRR: +$50K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Expansion MRR: +$20K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Churned MRR: -$15K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Contraction MRR: -$5K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Ending MRR: $550K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARR = $550K × 12 = $6.6M
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is MRR growth from new customers or expansion?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is churn/contraction increasing as you grow?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- What's the ratio of new:expansion:churn MRR? (Best: expansion > new)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Net Revenue = Gross Revenue - Discounts - Refunds - Credits
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Gross Revenue: $100K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Discounts: -$10K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Refunds: -$2K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Net Revenue: $88K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Are discounts >20%? (Pricing power problem)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Are refunds >10%? (Product quality problem)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Do certain channels have higher discount/refund rates?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Logo Churn Rate = Customers Lost / Starting Customers × 100
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Revenue Churn Rate = MRR Lost / Starting MRR × 100
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example (Logo Churn):**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Starting Customers: 1,000
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Customers Lost: 30
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Logo Churn = 30 / 1,000 = 3% monthly
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example (Revenue Churn):**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Starting MRR: $500K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- MRR Lost: $15K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Revenue Churn = $15K / $500K = 3% monthly
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is churn rate accelerating or decelerating over time?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Are newer cohorts churning faster than older ones? (PMF degradation)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is revenue churn higher than logo churn? (Losing big customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Convert monthly to annual:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Monthly churn compounds: 3% monthly ≠ 36% annual
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Formula: `Annual Churn = 1 - (1 - Monthly Churn)^12`
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- 3% monthly = ~31% annual churn
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|NRR = (Starting ARR + Expansion - Churn - Contraction) / Starting ARR × 100
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Starting ARR: $5M
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Expansion: +$800K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Churn: -$300K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Contraction: -$100K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Ending ARR from cohort: $5.4M
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- NRR = $5.4M / $5M = 108%
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is NRR >100%? (You grow without new logos)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is NRR improving or degrading cohort-over-cohort?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- What's driving NRR? (Expansion or low churn?)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Expansion Revenue = Upsells + Cross-sells + Usage Growth (from existing customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Upsells to higher tier: $50K/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Cross-sells of add-ons: $20K/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Usage growth: $10K/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Total Expansion Revenue: $80K/month
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is expansion revenue growing as % of total revenue?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- What % of customers expand each year? (Expansion rate)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Are certain cohorts/segments more likely to expand?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Quick Ratio = (New MRR + Expansion MRR) / (Churned MRR + Contraction MRR)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- New MRR: $50K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Expansion MRR: $20K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Churned MRR: $15K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Contraction MRR: $5K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Quick Ratio = ($50K + $20K) / ($15K + $5K) = $70K / $20K = 3.5
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Quick Ratio >4 = excellent (gains far exceed losses)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Quick Ratio 2-4 = healthy (sustainable growth)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Quick Ratio <2 = leaky bucket (fix retention before scaling)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Product/Segment % = Product/Segment Revenue / Total Revenue × 100
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|```
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Product A Revenue: $300K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Product B Revenue: $500K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Product C Revenue: $200K
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Total Revenue: $1M
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Product A: 30%, Product B: 50%, Product C: 20%
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Is revenue concentration increasing? (Risk: over-reliance on one product)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Which products are growing/shrinking?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Does revenue mix match your strategic priorities?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Group customers by when they joined and track metrics over time.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Example:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Cohort | Month 0 | Month 1 | Month 2 | Month 3 | Month 6 |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics||--------|---------|---------|---------|---------|---------|
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Jan 2024 | 100% | 95% | 92% | 90% | 85% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Feb 2024 | 100% | 94% | 90% | 87% | 80% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Mar 2024 | 100% | 92% | 86% | 82% | - |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Quality checks:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Are recent cohorts retaining better or worse than older cohorts?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- If worse: Product-market fit is degrading (fix before scaling)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- If better: Improvements are working (safe to scale)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Track revenue retention by cohort, not just logo retention
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|Before reporting metrics, validate:
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Revenue metrics:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Gross vs. net revenue clearly labeled
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Revenue growth rate > cost growth rate
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ ARPU/ARPA trends analyzed by cohort (not just blended)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Retention metrics:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Logo churn and revenue churn both tracked
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Cohort-over-cohort trends analyzed (not just blended churn)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ NRR tracked with components (expansion, churn, contraction)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Cohort analysis shows retention trends
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Revenue mix shows concentration risk
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Quick ratio shows growth sustainability
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|See `examples/` folder for detailed scenarios. Mini examples below:
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Company:** Mid-market project management SaaS
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Revenue Metrics:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- MRR: $2M (growing 10% month-over-month)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARR: $24M
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPA: $1,200/month (200 accounts)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPU: $120/month (20,000 users)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Average seats: 100 per account
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Retention Metrics:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Monthly logo churn: 2%
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Revenue churn: 1.5% (losing smaller customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- NRR: 115% (strong expansion)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Expansion revenue: $200K/month (10% of MRR)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Quick Ratio: 5.0
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Strong growth (10% MoM MRR)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Excellent retention (2% logo churn, 115% NRR)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Healthy expansion (NRR >100%)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Sustainable (Quick Ratio 5.0)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ Revenue churn < logo churn (losing smaller customers, good signal)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Action:** Scale acquisition. Unit economics are strong.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Company:** SMB mkt automation SaaS
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Revenue Metrics:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- MRR: $500K (growing 15% month-over-month)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARR: $6M
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPA: $250/month (2,000 accounts)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ARPU: $50/month (10,000 users)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Retention Metrics:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Monthly logo churn: 6% (increasing from 4% six months ago)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Revenue churn: 7% (losing larger customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- NRR: 85% (contracting)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Expansion revenue: $5K/month (1% of MRR)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Quick Ratio: 1.2
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Cohort Analysis:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Cohort | Month 6 Retention |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics||--------|-------------------|
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| 6 months ago | 75% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| 3 months ago | 65% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Current | 58% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ⚠️ High churn (6% monthly = ~50% annual)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- 🚨 Revenue churn > logo churn (losing bigger customers)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- 🚨 NRR <100% (contracting, not expanding)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- 🚨 Cohort degradation (newer customers churn faster)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- 🚨 Quick Ratio 1.2 (leaky bucket)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Action:** STOP scaling acquisition. Fix retention first. Investigate:
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Why are newer cohorts churning faster?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Why is expansion revenue only 1% of MRR?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- What's causing customer contraction?
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Company:** Multi-product SaaS platform
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Blended Metrics Look Great:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- MRR: $3M (growing 20% MoM)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Blended churn: 3%
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- Blended NRR: 110%
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**But Revenue Mix Analysis Shows:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Product | Revenue | % of Total | Growth | Churn | NRR |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics||---------|---------|------------|--------|-------|-----|
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| Legacy Product | $2M | 67% | -5% MoM | 8% | 75% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|| New Product | $1M | 33% | +80% MoM | 1% | 150% |
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Analysis:**
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- 🚨 Legacy product (67% of revenue) is dying: -5% growth, 8% churn, 75% NRR
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ✅ New product is stellar: +80% growth, 1% churn, 150% NRR
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ⚠️ Blended metrics hide the fact that 2/3 of revenue is contracting
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- ⚠️ High dependency on one product (67% concentration risk)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Action:** Accelerate migration from legacy to new product. Plan for legacy product sunset.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "We grew revenue 50% this year, we're crushing it!"
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Revenue is the top line, not bottom line. You might be growing at a loss, destroying margins, or scaling unprofitable products.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Always pair revenue metrics with margin metrics (see `saas-economics-efficiency-metrics`). $1M revenue at 80% margin >> $2M revenue at 20% margin.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "ARPU increased 30%!" (but customer count dropped 40%)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** ARPU rose because you lost all your small customers, not because you improved monetization.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Analyze ARPU by cohort and segment. True ARPU improvement = same customers paying more, not losing cheap customers.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "Blended churn is stable at 3%"
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Blended metrics can hide that new cohorts churn at 6% while old cohorts churn at 1%. Product-market fit is degrading.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Always analyze retention by cohort. If newer cohorts perform worse, stop scaling and fix the product.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "Logo churn is only 2%, we're great!"
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** You might be losing 2% of customers but 10% of revenue if you're churning large customers.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Track both logo churn AND revenue churn. If revenue churn > logo churn, you're losing high-value customers.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "We lost 50 customers this month" (no ctx on who)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Losing 50 small customers ($10/month) is different from losing 50 enterprise customers ($10K/month).
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Segment churn analysis by customer size, cohort, and reason. Weight by revenue impact, not just logo count.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "3% monthly churn is fine, that's only 36% annually"
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Churn compounds. 3% monthly = 31% annual churn, not 36%. Math: `1 - (1 - 0.03)^12 = 31%`.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Use the correct formula when converting monthly to annual churn. Don't just multiply by 12.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "Gross revenue is up 20%!" (but discounts/refunds doubled)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Net revenue might be flat or shrinking. Discounts hide pricing power problems; refunds hide product quality issues.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Always track gross AND net revenue. If discounts >20% or refunds >10%, investigate why.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "NRR is 105%, we're expanding!"
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** NRR can be >100% just from very low churn, without meaningful expansion. True expansion-driven NRR is >120%.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Break down NRR into components: expansion MRR vs. churned/contracted MRR. Aim for expansion-driven NRR, not just low churn.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "We're at $10M ARR!" (but $5M is from one customer)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Losing that one customer cuts revenue in half. Roadmap becomes hostage to one customer's requests.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Track revenue concentration. Ideal: Top customer <10% of revenue, Top 10 customers <40%. Diversify early.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Symptom:** "Our ARPU is $100" (average of $10 SMB and $1,000 enterprise)
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Consequence:** Blended ARPU hides segment economics. Can't make smart acquisition or product decisions.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|**Fix:** Calculate ARPU/ARPA by segment (SMB, mid-market, enterprise). Optimize each segment independently.
M|saas-revenue-growth-metrics|- `saas-economics-efficiency-metrics` — Unit economics (CAC, LTV, margins, burn rate)
